description.plain:
Big Shaq is a character played by British comedian Michael Dapaah. He has featured in multiple online skits before going viral through his “Fire in the Booth” freestyle.

Though commonly referred to as a parody of Grime, this is actually false. Big Shaq is a parody of UK Drill and “roadman” culture, hence why most of his songs have UK Drill beats, not grime beats. Grime is a fast electronic genre typically around 137-142 bpm. UK Drill is similar though far darker and takes a lot more influence from Chicago Drill & trap music.

description.plain:
Released after the viral success of his freestyle on the BBC Radio 1 series Fire in the Booth, British comedian Michael Dapaah converted it into an official song titled “Man’s Not Hot” under the name Big Shaq, a parody character of the British “roadmen” culture.

The song was released under Island Records on September 22, 2017.

It has since spawned an official remix featuring notable British rappers Lethal Bizzle, Chip, Krept & Konan and Jme.

songs.full_title: Fire in the Booth by Big Shaq
songs.title: Fire in the Booth

description.plain:
British comedian Michael Dapaah plays the roles of MC Quakez and Roadman Shaq in his Fire in the Booth freestyle. It is the second Fire in the Booth performed by a comedian after 2015’s R.S.

Dapaah begins the freestyle as MC Quakez, an aspiring UK rapper who thinks he has bars but doesn’t realise how bad he is, continuously missing the drop during the first half of the freestyle.

MC Quakez and his partner Shakes then exit for Roadman Shaq (also played by Dapaah) to take over the booth to spit over 67’s “Let’s Lurk”.
